9
 An eighteenth-century note by Thomas Astle in Stowe 39 attributes The Abbey to John Alcock (fol.2r),
but the biography of Alcock provided on the same folio disproves this possibility, as Alcock lived in the
very late fifteenth-century, over a hundred years after The Abbey was first translated from English, and fifty
years after Stowe 39 was likely compiled. The Corpus Christi College MS also attributes The Abbey to
Alcock (Consacro "An Edition" cxxxi). Lambeth Palace MS. 432, fol. 34v attributes the text to "Richard
hampspull," but Hope Emily Allen disproved this possibility of Richard Rolle as author in 1927, the main
reason being that while there was a general tendency in the Middle Ages to attach Rolle's name to his
works, the Lambeth MS is the only manuscript containing The Abbey to do so ("The Abbey of the Holy
Ghost" 337). As Leo Carruthers notes, often "Rolle's prestige led copyists to attach his name to popular
religious texts of unknown provenance," which would explain the spurious Lambeth attribution (213). 
